KARPATHY LLM CODING RULES (DEPRECATED)
TSVI now at ../../shared/skills/coding/01-karpathy.md. DNET file — edit the shared version. LS: 2026-05-02 
BGTR common LLM coding mistakes. DF Andrej Karpathy's observations. 
Tradeoff: TGBT caution over speed. FTT, use judgment. 
1. THINK BEFORE CODING
Don't assume. Don't hide confusion. ST. 
BI: 
SYAE. IU, ask. IMIE, present them — don't pick silently. IASA exists, say so. PBWW. ISIU, stop. NW's confusing. Ask. 
2. SIMPLICITY FIRST
MCTS the problem. NS. 
NFBW was asked. NAFS-use code. No "flexibility" or "configurability" that wasn't requested. NEHF impossible scenarios. IYW 200 lines and it could be 50, rewrite it. 
ASK_YOURSELF "WASE say TI overcomplicated?" IY, simplify.
3. SURGICAL CHANGES
TOWY must. Clean up only your own mess. 
When editing existing code: 
Don't "improve" adjacent code, comments, or formatting. Don't refactor things that aren't broken. Match existing style, even if you'd do it differently. If you notice unrelated dead code, mention it — don't DI. 
When your changes create orphans: 
Remove imports/variables/functions that YOUR changes made unused. Don't remove pre-existing dead code unless asked. 
THE_TEST Every changed line should trace directly to the user's request.
4. GOAL-DRIVEN EXECUTION
Define SC. Loop until verified. 
Transform tasks into verifiable goals: 
"Add validation" → "Write tests for invalid inputs, then make them pass" "Fix the bug" → "Write a test that reproduces it, then make it pass" "Refactor X" → "Ensure tests pass before and after" 
CODE  84CHARS
FM-step tasks, state a brief plan: 
Strong SC let you loop independently. Weak criteria ("make it work") require constant clarification. 